The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Worbus helpline for small units in east

 A STAFF REPORTER

 George Molakal in Calcutta on Tuesday. A Telegraph picture

 Calcutta, Nov. 21: North America-based management consultancy and investment firm Worbus International LLC has lined up $500 million to invest in small and medium enterprises in India over the next two to three years. Of this, $300 million could be invested in SMEs in the eastern region.

 We have identified Howrah, Haldia, Durgapur, Siliguri, Bhubaneswar and some other places in the eastern region to start with, said George Molakal, international director of Worbus International LLC. We have carried out a primary study and we may require to invest $150 million in the first year, he added. The company plans to invest $200 million in SMEs in the north.

 Worbus, which has operations in Bangalore, Mumbai and Pune for the past one-and-a-half years, is now entering the eastern and northern regions in association with India Trade Centre Private Ltd, a Delhi-based consulting firm. India Trade primarily caters to foreign companies that plan to set up operations in India.

 Worbus specialises in finding alliances for North American and other foreign companies for merger and acquisitions, strategic alliances, joint ventures, collaborations and manufacturing outsourcing in emerging markets. Besides, Worbus also arranges for private equity investments for SMEs.

 We have completed 25 projects in India, mainly in the southern and western parts during the past one-and-a-half years. We now have 70 projects in hand, Molakal said. The 25 projects accounted for a total equity investment of $125 million by Worbus alone and manufacturing contract worth $600 million. The 70 projects that are underway will entail joint venture deals aggregating $500 million and private equity investment of $1 billion, Molakal said, adding that Worbus didnt pick up more than 24 per cent of the total equity of the SMEs in which it invested. 

 According to Molakal, the company has found joint venture partners for the Nusli Wadia groups metal alloy business and the Yash Birla groups Zenith Pipes. 




